WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.900
sub-time shock and the recovery of world economy and science and technology should play a role.

00:07.380 --> 00:12.740
And I said there should be no time for nationalism, for Japanese strategy.

00:13.060 --> 00:20.980
We should really open up. This is a great moment for Japan to design post catch-up world model

00:20.980 --> 00:27.220
with more openness to the world and hence I said there is no time for nationalism.

00:27.220 --> 00:29.340
Thank you very much for your attention.

00:38.820 --> 00:47.860
Another window of hope with the no nationalism is the tsunami and thank you for the inauguration of the new term science diplomacy.

00:48.100 --> 00:50.000
There is no better place to start with that.

00:50.000 --> 01:01.240
Now, Professor Pradeep, President Pradeep will deliver a speech on Japan's role within and beyond the crisis.

01:02.160 --> 01:09.000
Being the last, it's lucky and unlucky at the same time. You may also draw some conclusion, Professor Pradeep.

01:10.760 --> 01:16.200
This was I'm asking for. I don't know if I'm able to do it, you know.

01:16.940 --> 01:26.560
But first of all I have really to thank the Japanese ambassador, Mr. Kono, because he invited me

01:26.560 --> 01:34.020
and with Osservatorio Asia organized this meeting that I have found very, very fruitful.

01:34.020 --> 01:44.160
And we have also to, we have the responsibility to take the consequence of the teaching that we had today.

01:46.280 --> 01:53.440
Now I am trying to sum up, to draw some conclusion of what we listened today

01:53.440 --> 02:01.340
and to make some comparison between the European and Italian situation, the Japanese one.

02:04.020 --> 02:14.720
First of all we had a comparison between the twin deficit, Italian and Japanese, very, very useful.

02:17.200 --> 02:24.340
But with a remarkable difference that gives you the idea in which crisis we live.

02:24.340 --> 02:32.300
First of all, in absolute and relative terms, the Japanese deficit is much higher than the Italian.

02:32.740 --> 02:42.780
But as you have listened, 95% is owned by Japanese. And so it's not under attack.

02:42.780 --> 02:58.860
There is a big difference. There is the possibility of having, taking the political decision that you listed before, increasing taxation.

03:01.360 --> 03:12.120
So I don't know if it will be possible to take that because you can tell this because you are not running for elections,

03:12.120 --> 03:19.220
because otherwise it will be difficult to announce this increase in taxation as you announced before.

03:19.880 --> 03:29.900
But in any case, being independent from the big financial world, you have time to decide and to handle your policy.

03:29.900 --> 03:39.620
This is a lesson for Italy and for all people who really push it for the globalization of financial markets.

03:43.040 --> 03:52.880
Let's say the sense of avoiding risk that being in a big financial market gives, this is absolutely not true.

03:52.880 --> 04:01.240
We have Italy is in risk in the sense that I don't think that is a real risk.

04:01.440 --> 04:11.760
But anyway, it's close to the risk, is reputed to the financial market for the risk only because our debt is not owned by Italians.

04:13.040 --> 04:17.280
And this is a reflection that we have to do.

04:17.280 --> 04:22.400
Second general reflection, a question mark also.

04:23.400 --> 04:31.060
It's quite interesting that you complained about the increase of the yen and the problem that is given.

04:31.660 --> 04:44.900
And it's very interesting because in this strange world you always lose the sovereignty on the rate of exchange.

04:46.000 --> 04:59.100
Even if you are inside the euro or if you are not inside the euro, when there are behavior of the big players in the financial market like we have now,

04:59.540 --> 05:09.760
it's difficult that you can manage your rate of exchange in the most convenient way for your initial policy.

05:09.760 --> 05:17.880
I think that this is a general lesson that we have to learn by your teaching today.

05:21.500 --> 05:25.840
Well, I have also been happy because of your statistics.

05:27.760 --> 05:32.540
The primary surplus was the best behavior was under my government.

05:32.540 --> 05:39.840
We were not in agreement before, but I'd be happy to read that.

05:41.040 --> 05:45.480
But you posed a strong question.

05:45.620 --> 05:50.600
Why the ring fence has not been applied to Greece by Europe?

05:51.720 --> 05:54.600
But look, there is no rational answer.

05:55.600 --> 06:11.540
It's only a political answer because when Greece started to shake, it was enough to have 30 billion euros to stop it.

06:11.700 --> 06:14.500
Now 10 times more is not sufficient.

06:15.340 --> 06:21.720
And so it's difficult that I answer your question in a rational way.

06:21.720 --> 06:37.320
Simply, we have a Europe that is half-cooked and the supernatural powers are not sufficient to take decisions in this difficult environment.

06:38.220 --> 06:44.660
And so the decision has been taken by the national government, mainly in this case by Germany.

06:44.660 --> 06:54.700
And the electorate was not eager to help countries in need.

06:55.200 --> 07:01.940
There was a political situation that made this difficult.

07:01.940 --> 07:08.620
And still now, you see, the European policy is going in the right direction.

07:09.520 --> 07:17.800
But because of the behavior of the electorate is slow and insufficient in quantity.

07:18.560 --> 07:21.020
Right direction, but slow, you know.

07:21.240 --> 07:26.180
The aid to Greece, it comes always late and always insufficient.

07:26.180 --> 07:33.400
So the international market, they never say, OK, we understand that there is a ring fence, as you ask.

07:33.960 --> 07:37.020
And they try again and try again and try again.

07:37.360 --> 07:38.860
But this is politics, you know.

07:40.220 --> 07:46.260
When we started the euro, I do remember the dialogue with the Chancellor of Corsica.

07:46.500 --> 07:54.860
Because, you know, I was president of the Commission and I raised the problem of, look, we have a common currency, we need a common taxation.

07:54.860 --> 07:56.220
Ring fence.

07:56.860 --> 08:00.180
And the answer was wise from the political point of view.

08:00.460 --> 08:05.000
The answer was, look, we did such a big effort in building up the euro.

08:05.420 --> 08:11.560
It was so difficult to stop with the Deutsche Mark that now, please, we should do it later.

08:12.060 --> 08:21.540
But then we had a period of change in which Italians or Germans were afraid about globalization,

08:21.540 --> 08:28.200
were afraid about Chinese competition, were afraid about immigration, were afraid about everything.

08:28.700 --> 08:33.400
And so the decision of the ring fence has not been organized.

08:34.220 --> 08:35.380
This is the situation of Europe.

08:35.820 --> 08:40.700
But I am not surprised because Europe has always developed through crisis.

08:41.160 --> 08:47.380
If you look at the history of Europe, and then, you know, it's a fantastic challenge.

08:47.680 --> 08:49.080
It's a fantastic challenge.

08:49.080 --> 08:55.140
We shall go on another 50 years to complete it, you know, or maybe more.

08:55.440 --> 08:59.640
But this is, we have no options.

08:59.780 --> 09:11.320
So this is why I am also sure that the euro will not collapse, you know, because there is no interest of any European country to do it, you know.

09:12.940 --> 09:15.340
The German surface is unbelievable.

09:15.340 --> 09:20.460
The real China in the world is Germany, it's not China, you know.

09:21.700 --> 09:36.800
And so we shall have all this problem of waving, but no disruption of the euro will be because there is not interest of anybody.

09:36.800 --> 09:45.780
Then you raise the big change in population and, you know, demography matters.

09:46.480 --> 09:58.980
I think that if you are wise, demography matters a little less than we fear, in the sense that, you know,

09:58.980 --> 10:07.960
the average age increases, but the health of people is not the same than the generation before.

10:09.200 --> 10:14.100
So clearly you have to move the pension system and to have to adapt the health system.

10:15.800 --> 10:24.220
But a human being 50 years ago, being 50 years old is not a human being of today being 50 years old.

10:24.220 --> 10:30.320
And so we have not to be so mathematical, you know, to describe this.

10:31.120 --> 10:42.600
Of course we have to adapt the system, but this, I tell you that from this point of view, Italy is absolutely in a perfect situation, you know.

10:42.600 --> 10:55.040
With the last reforms for 30 years we shall not have any imbalance and any major increase in the pension costs, you know.

10:55.460 --> 11:05.240
And it was painful, it was difficult, but this has been done, you know.

11:05.240 --> 11:12.680
There is a difference, clearly, between Japan and Europe, is immigration, you know.

11:14.060 --> 11:17.360
You have shown that to take care of old people you have robots.

11:18.060 --> 11:20.920
We have women coming from East Europe called badanti.

11:21.700 --> 11:24.940
There is a big difference. The robots have no children.

11:26.860 --> 11:30.960
The women coming from East Europe, they may have children, you know.

11:30.960 --> 11:36.220
And so they may change demography and the robots cannot change demography.

11:36.860 --> 11:46.160
And this is something that is very, very important and it makes Japan different from other countries.

11:46.160 --> 12:03.240
Of course you fall into the cultural problem raised by Professor Maffei, you know, because he really stresses the uniqueness of Japan in history, you know.

12:03.600 --> 12:11.300
And with immigration you lose this uniqueness, but is it an advantage or a disadvantage?

12:11.860 --> 12:13.320
This is another problem, you know.

12:13.460 --> 12:18.360
We have no choice because our immigrants come in any case and so we have no political choice.

12:19.100 --> 12:23.360
But you have a choice, but it is a choice, you know.

12:23.360 --> 12:41.880
And I think that this will influence heavily, can influence heavily the problem of aging of Japan, of any country.

12:43.820 --> 12:52.700
But anyway, we also understood the other great difference, how big is your effort on innovation?

12:53.480 --> 12:57.700
And this makes a great difference in favor of Japan, you know.

12:57.700 --> 13:11.920
If you perform this plan in spite of the public deficit, putting a lot of money on innovation, I think that you are in the right track.

13:12.260 --> 13:13.880
And this is a difference with Italy.

13:14.860 --> 13:24.260
We have decreased our R&D expenditure that was already low enough because of financial constraints.

13:24.260 --> 13:27.400
But here we are in a completely different strategy.

13:28.240 --> 13:33.040
In this case I do back the Japanese strategy, not the Italian one.

13:33.260 --> 13:40.360
In immigration is the reverse, but anyway this is my personal opinion, you know.

13:40.860 --> 13:52.000
And your policy on innovation will be the real asset of Japan.

13:52.000 --> 14:11.160
But taking another short observation, the Japanese history in the recent time has been very unique because you have been leading for one generation at least.

14:12.200 --> 14:18.440
And the world model was Japan and in the end of the 80s there was this change, you know.

14:18.440 --> 14:32.260
The book of Morita Akio on Japan was able to say no, how was it taken in the United States, you know.

14:33.180 --> 14:44.720
And then the stagnation came, or the slow growth came, and clearly it is difficult to explain.

14:44.720 --> 14:54.760
Because all the phenomena that you explained, aging and so on, they are much slower than the change of the direction of Japanese policy.

14:55.360 --> 15:09.760
So I do think that political mistakes also were done, or not adequate evaluation of the changing of the world, you know.

15:09.760 --> 15:17.420
The bubble of the 90s was certainly a mistake, a political mistake in my opinion, you know.

15:19.540 --> 15:31.220
Now I have no other figures to analyze it, but clearly looking with a historical perspective this was the moment of the Japanese switch.

15:36.820 --> 15:54.220
But this is very understood and I don't want to stop it, but I want to stress one evolution that I think is important.

15:55.280 --> 16:12.600
Japan, in spite of the slow growth or accompanying the growth or allowing the growth, the slow growth rate, has exported a lot of manufacturing during this period of stagnation.

16:12.600 --> 16:33.520
And you have become a big manufacturer abroad, with two consequences, having then a positive flow of income from your investment abroad, but even more opening new links.

16:33.520 --> 16:39.080
And the new links are Asian links, not American or European links.

16:39.740 --> 16:54.880
So I found Japan today very different from Japan yesterday, and my observation is that now Japan is an Asian country.

16:56.240 --> 17:11.520
In the sense that if you look at trade, if you look at cross investment, China is your biggest importer, number one, and it was absolutely unbelievable, unbelievable in the recent past.

17:12.040 --> 17:22.060
And then I think that these links have become more and stronger and stronger and stronger and stronger.

17:22.060 --> 17:23.600
I give you an example.

17:26.360 --> 17:37.140
One year ago when you had the terrible tsunami, the consequence was to stop an unbelievable number of Chinese factories.

17:37.140 --> 17:48.140
You know, for months and months, why? Because the high-tech supplies went from Japan, and the links is also the reverse.

17:48.640 --> 17:56.480
In the flood of Thailand, a lot of Japanese suppliers suffered because they had no more the market for them.

17:56.480 --> 18:06.760
And without any deliberate policy, but because of the growth of Asia, you will become more and more Asian.

18:08.080 --> 18:14.240
And I think that this will have also an enormous political consequence.

18:14.860 --> 18:27.420
I'm only guessing, but when you are linked in a new economic environment, step by step you go also into a different political environment, you know.

18:27.420 --> 18:42.520
And after the centuries of isolation that you explained, after they link with Germany, with the major revolution, and the United States in the after world period,

18:43.060 --> 18:53.920
I think that is starting a period in which you must deploy a strong inter-Asian link because this is the market, this is the link,

18:53.920 --> 18:58.120
this is the challenge that Japan has now.

18:58.800 --> 19:12.720
Clearly this brings a challenge in relation with Europe because I think that you need Europe to counterbalance this change of history.

19:13.440 --> 19:16.800
And we need Japan for the same sake, you know.

19:16.800 --> 19:32.600
But if you analyze the summits, the meeting between the European Union and Japan, we discuss very interesting things, you know, non-tariff barriers and so on.

19:32.600 --> 19:59.740
But there is no sense of history in the sense that there is no deep thought on these long-term events, how to, let's say, adapt our relation to this new history that is, in my opinion, is absolutely impossible to avoid, you know.

19:59.740 --> 20:09.920
And this, I think, will be the challenge that we have as Italy today here, as Europe tomorrow in Brussels, I don't know.

20:09.920 --> 20:37.480
But to understand that this change in real things must make us thinking to the political future with more freedom than we have now, you know, because we cannot, let's say, restrict the problems between Europe and Japan to the non-tariff barriers, you know.

20:37.480 --> 20:41.940
Well, of course they are important, you know, but there is something more.

20:42.380 --> 20:52.300
There is how to build a future together or, you know, to take the consequence of being separate, you know.

20:52.300 --> 21:18.660
This is last small observation is concerning the Japanese, it's more a question than, of course, an opinion because I am not a specialist on Japan, you know, but I have been taken by the Japanese behavior after the tsunami.

21:20.100 --> 21:37.040
Because it's a counter that, from the economic point of view, I am an economist, you know, has demonstrated to have a resilience and the ability to change that is fantastic, you know, but also an absolute new challenge, you know.

21:37.040 --> 21:57.160
I did remember two years ago, you are more able to define the precise date, the Japanese government made the message, we shall arrive to 50% of nuclear energy from 3035, you know.

21:57.160 --> 22:11.560
Let's say new strategy, nuclear. Then you have a terrible accident, a complete change of mind, a new political debate and now the necessity of a new policy.

22:11.560 --> 22:28.960
And this, as far as I know, will be decided by you and your minister in the next month, but now what is absolutely remarkable is how Japan has adapted to the lack of energy.

22:28.960 --> 22:54.820
You know, distributing, decreasing consumption, distributing it during the week, night, day, adapting, and so has been able in a few months to make factories resurrect and the production, let's say, not to be normalized, but almost normalized, you know.

22:56.800 --> 23:11.520
But the long-term changes are there, you know. Japan will spend at least 35 billion euros more on energy import now.

23:11.520 --> 23:37.720
Then I don't know which policy will be adopted, you know, but if the nuclear power station remains closed, as they are now all but two and they will be all closed in a few months, if this goes on, you have to spend it immediately because you need time to implement the alternative energy project.

23:37.720 --> 23:45.260
So this is, in my opinion, a very, very, very difficult time.

23:45.260 --> 24:11.580
But to sum up all this today, the real new fact that there is a big new supply chain in the world that we cannot call it Japanese, we cannot call it Chinese, we must call it Asian.

24:11.580 --> 24:41.560
And this is the change of the world. So deep that two weeks ago, when the managers of Apple, they came to President Obama to present a new strategy, you know, and they told that they will robotize the Fox Coalitions.

24:44.020 --> 25:00.560
Of course, the answer of the President was, look, now the added value, the labor added value in the iPad and the iPhone is almost negligible, let's say.

25:00.560 --> 25:21.920
$70 for iPad or $20 and $10 for iPhone, you know, and then if you robotize, it will decrease more and more and we will arrive to two, three percent of the value of the product.

25:21.920 --> 25:36.300
So why you don't bring the production to California? And the answer was because now the supply chain, the Asia supply chain is absolutely unique in the world.

25:36.300 --> 25:57.580
And it's not a problem of cost. The quick response to the change, the organization, let's say the intermediate skilled organizers of the labor, they are now a resource that we find only in Asia.

25:57.580 --> 26:17.020
And this is, in my opinion, what is happening, that clearly Japan must take the consequence of this change. And because of scientific level, because of your knowledge of your organization, you must exploit this happening.

26:36.680 --> 26:40.260
Inside the new reality.

26:40.260 --> 26:48.360
E, ovviamente, nella luce di questo cambiamento, noi europei e gli americani, di loro,

26:48.940 --> 26:55.640
dobbiamo completamente cambiare la strategia che abbiamo tra noi.

26:56.240 --> 27:02.300
Queste sono le mie reflezioni, e vi ringrazio per la lezione che avete dato a noi.

27:12.300 --> 27:17.260
Grazie al professor Prodi, sembra che la globalizzazione sia l'epitome di complessità.

27:19.100 --> 27:26.560
Ora, prima di che la santa vada completamente giù, abbiamo un po' di minuti per qualche domanda che potete avere.

27:27.660 --> 27:37.040
Quindi, se c'è un'altra domanda, riuscite a riscaldare la sua o la sua mano e posate la domanda, se potete.

27:40.280 --> 27:41.680
Sì.

27:45.560 --> 27:48.140
Potete provare a parlare?

27:49.280 --> 27:51.260
A svegliare?

27:59.600 --> 28:02.820
Sì, venite qui. Venite qui.

28:16.040 --> 28:21.700
Grazie molto. Sono un giornalista, e ora voglio chiedere un'altra domanda.

28:22.980 --> 28:31.660
Il professor Prodi ha detto che l'azione reale, l'Asia, è il nuovo fattore della politica mondiale.

28:33.500 --> 28:37.340
Ho la stessa opinione, sono stato per molti anni in Giappone come giornalista,

28:38.380 --> 28:40.240
e ho trovato questo molto interessante.

28:41.200 --> 28:49.540
Ma per Giappone questo pose una grande domanda, perché la priorità dei Stati Uniti,

28:49.600 --> 28:54.240
la relazione con Giappone, forse deve cambiare.

28:55.960 --> 29:01.240
E quindi, questo è un problema molto grande, non solo per Giappone, ma anche per l'Europa.

29:01.680 --> 29:07.760
E vorrei sapere l'opinione della gente giapponese su questo grande problema,

29:08.960 --> 29:15.260
perché questa strida relazione tra Giappone e gli Stati Uniti

29:15.260 --> 29:22.120
ha in qualche modo evitato a Giappone di giocare un ruolo molto grande nell'Asia.

29:22.840 --> 29:29.860
Ma questo ruolo è inevitabile, quindi vorrei avere la vostra opinione su questo.

29:30.860 --> 29:38.920
Sì, non è facile, ma prima di tutto, per rispondere a questa domanda,

29:39.220 --> 29:45.860
bisogna pensare sulla strategia americana nel posto Pacifico.

29:46.740 --> 29:53.860
E ci sono molte contraddizioni, anche su questo, perché in teoria,

29:54.840 --> 29:58.880
gli americani vogliono isolare la Cina.

30:00.460 --> 30:06.280
President Obama visita tutti i paesi in Cina, non Cina,

30:07.140 --> 30:09.140
e la Missa Clinton fa lo stesso.

30:11.100 --> 30:16.480
E, diciamo, nel ritorno alla campagna dell'elezione,

30:16.820 --> 30:21.240
la Cina sarà un'assetta.

30:21.240 --> 30:26.780
Ma è come la situazione europea sull'euro.

30:27.000 --> 30:33.720
La comunità di negozio non vuole nemmeno avere questo comportamento.

30:34.160 --> 30:40.660
Quindi parlano alto, ma l'azione non è così forte.

30:41.100 --> 30:48.710
Quindi penso che, perché questo, c'è molto ruolo di manovra per Giappone.

30:48.710 --> 30:52.810
C'è molta libertà in questo senso.

30:56.870 --> 31:00.870
Non viviamo nella situazione del 20-25 anni fa.

31:01.990 --> 31:08.010
Gli Stati Uniti hanno un grande potere, ma il più grande potere del mondo,

31:08.110 --> 31:12.130
è che non possono agire solo.

31:13.130 --> 31:16.470
E quindi, da questo punto di vista,

31:16.890 --> 31:23.650
Giappone, ovviamente, rimane un amico forte e loyale dei Stati Uniti,

31:25.130 --> 31:33.510
ma ha molto ruolo di manovra che Giappone non aveva prima.

31:33.970 --> 31:39.110
Ma perché questa è la nuova politica del mondo, è la stessa cosa per l'Europa,

31:39.110 --> 31:41.970
non la usiamo perché siamo divisi,

31:42.350 --> 31:45.050
ma il ruolo di manovra per l'Europa

31:45.050 --> 31:52.110
potrebbe essere molto, molto più alto che il ruolo che esploitiamo ora.

31:56.610 --> 31:59.590
Abbiamo spazio, il professor Onida.

32:02.830 --> 32:04.790
Una domanda al professor Ito.

32:04.790 --> 32:08.410
Prendendo il risultato del 95% dei salari giapponesi

32:08.410 --> 32:11.730
che sono stati ai salari giapponesi,

32:12.630 --> 32:15.310
a causa dell'integrazione dei mercati finanziari,

32:15.330 --> 32:22.130
cosa evita i salari giapponesi di diversificare un po' il loro portogiovole?

32:22.230 --> 32:28.250
Per esempio, per sostituire alcuni dei bondi a lungo termine da Giappone,

32:28.250 --> 32:31.650
che sovraggono, credo, 2%,

32:31.650 --> 32:35.290
magari con alcuni bondi italiani a lungo termine da Giappone,

32:35.310 --> 32:37.250
che sovraggono 5%.

32:41.070 --> 32:48.310
I salari giapponesi hanno provato i bondi a lungo termine da Giappone,

32:48.710 --> 32:51.870
come i bondi australiani, i bondi di New Zealand,

32:51.870 --> 32:57.010
e sono stati toccati, perché i bondi sono apprezzati,

32:58.170 --> 33:07.190
e la diprezzazione principale è stata molto più che una differenzione di interesse.

33:07.650 --> 33:13.670
Quindi sono diventati molto bianchi del rischio di currency.

33:13.670 --> 33:21.130
E questo è stato pagato in una crisi finanziaria mondiale.

33:21.990 --> 33:27.910
Gli istituti finanziari giapponesi sono stati toccati in strutture

33:28.670 --> 33:33.110
che le istituzioni finanziarie dell'U.S. sono stati a pressione

33:33.110 --> 33:38.030
e le istituzioni finanziarie europee sono stati a porto.

33:38.030 --> 33:44.990
Quindi è stato rinforzato che essere a casa sia sicuro.

33:46.370 --> 33:48.750
Questo è il sentimento dei loro istituti giapponesi.

33:52.330 --> 33:58.890
I stock giapponesi sono underperformati.

33:59.590 --> 34:05.890
Hanno perso un quarto dei valori da una crisi finanziaria mondiale.

34:05.890 --> 34:12.130
Per esempio, quando i prezzi sono sbagliati,

34:12.190 --> 34:14.430
la risposta reale è alta.

34:16.050 --> 34:19.850
Quindi la risposta del 1% dei bondi giapponesi

34:19.850 --> 34:23.390
sembra essere una risposta molto buona.

34:26.770 --> 34:31.850
Questa è la conclusione dei saveri giapponesi e dei saveri corporati.

34:31.850 --> 34:34.870
I saveri giapponesi sono anche spingiti.

34:35.670 --> 34:42.630
Quindi i paesi giapponesi e i portofogli corporati

34:42.630 --> 34:47.510
